fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Therefore, it remains to show that P is a proposition. Without loss of generality, we may assume that we have some h: P. By Corollary , we may fix x:A and prove that 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
,\epsilon 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\cong _{\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {refl}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 is a proposition. Of course, this is a retract of the identification type 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
,\epsilon 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
=_{\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {refl}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 and so by Lemma  it is enough to prove that the latter is a proposition. In fact, we will deduce this via Lemma  by observing that the fiber of f at fx is contractible: using our assumption h:P and the distributivity of products over sums, we may construct a retraction of f exhibiting f as biinvertible and thus by Corollary  contractible.

Without loss of generality, we may assume that f has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
. By Lemma , it suffices to argue that the type of inverses to f is a retract of a proposition; the type of inverses to f is in fact equivalent to the type of sections equipped with a coherent remainder:

By Lemma , it suffices to show that the type of sections to f is a proposition and that for every such section, the coherent remainder thereof is a proposition. The latter is Lemma , and the former follows from Lemma  by means of the retraction 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\eta \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

Univalence is more difficult to establish than for the case of left cleavings (Definition ). Fixing a:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
, we must show that the reflexive graph structure on 
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} a\right \rvert \mathclose {}
 with edges in b \approx _{\mathcal {B} a} \mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{a}^*b' and reflexivity data for b:Ba given by \Phi _B ab\colon  b\approx _{\mathcal {B} a}\mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{a}^*b is univalent.

It suffices to show that the type of singletons \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen b':
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} a\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen b':
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} a\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen b':
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} a\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen b':
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} a\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} b\approx _{\mathcal {B} a}\mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{a}^*b' is a proposition. As each \mathcal {B} a is univalent, this is easily shown to be a retract of \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen b':
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} a\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen b':
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} a\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen b':
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} a\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen b':
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} a\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} b\approx _{\mathcal {B} a}b', which is a proposition again by the univalence of \mathcal {B} a. Therefore, we conclude via Lemma .

Fixing x:B, we must show that \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}gx\approx _{\mathcal {A}}gy is a proposition. But this is a retract of  \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}gx\approx _{\mathcal {A}}y, which is a proposition by the univalence of \mathcal {A}; thus the result follows from the closure of propositions under retracts (Lemma ).
